300 316 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 365 699 (In private email, John Dlugosz wrote:) 699 SB
600 414 1425 (\223There is no provision for errors caused by implementation limits.  The class) 1425 SB
600 463 1445 (handles strings up to length NPOS-1, with no specified way to throw an error) 1445 SB
600 512 1500 (saying "I can't do that!" for shorter values.  In my implementation I'm simulating) 1500 SB
600 561 1489 (an out-of-memory error if an operation exceeds a `maxcount' length, since that's) 1489 SB
600 610 1312 (what would presumably happen anyway.  The maxcount arises due to) 1312 SB
600 659 1315 (arithmetic overflow:  I'm limited to size_t-\(small constant\) _bytes_, not) 1315 SB
600 708 1335 (elements, and an element may be any size.  I can't compute the memory) 1335 SB
600 757 1421 (requirments without getting an unreported arithmetic overflow, so I have to) 1421 SB
600 806 1066 (check in advance for this instantiation-specific maxcount.) 1066 SB
600 904 1423 (\223In order to simulate the out of memory condition, I just call `new' on NPOS) 1423 SB
600 953 1435 (bytes.  That way I get the "correct" behavior for any installed new_handler or) 1435 SB
600 1002 1350 (replacement operator new\(\) that may exist. However, that is not the best) 1350 SB
600 1051 1475 (solution for a few reasons.  First, it will fail if the implementation _does_ in fact) 1475 SB
600 1100 1480 (allocate NPOS bytes without error.  Second, an out-of-memory exception might) 1480 SB
600 1149 1473 (not be the appropriate way for a program to recover from this problem.  Third,) 1473 SB
600 1198 1434 (it is less efficient, since by spec I must test for an argument of NPOS anyway,) 1434 SB
600 1247 1459 (and take one action and _then_ test for the smaller maxcount and take another) 1459 SB
600 1296 1394 (action.  To summarize, I think that a "length error" should be allowed at an) 1394 SB
600 1345 1445 (implementation defined size limit which is less than or equal to NPOS.  There) 1445 SB
600 1394 1156 (should also be a function available to return this value.cause.\224) 1156 SB
300 1443 398 (Proposed Resolution:) 398 SB
