300 1493 95 (Title:) 95 SB
600 1493 792 (The error conditions are not well-specified) 792 SB
1392 1493 658 ( for the find\(\) and rfind\(\) functions.) 658 SB
300 1542 145 (Section:) 145 SB
600 1542 494 (21.1.1.4.20 [lib.string::find]) 494 SB
300 1591 125 (Status:) 125 SB
600 1591 110 (active) 110 SB
300 1640 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 1689 699 (In private email, John Dlugosz wrote:) 699 SB
600 1738 1368 (\223The error conditions are not very well specified for the find\(\) and rfind\(\)) 1368 SB
600 1787 1219 (functions, nor do I feel that they are the most appropriate  choice.) 1219 SB
600 1885 1030 (\223My interpretation of 21.1.1.4.20 [lib.string::find] is that) 1030 SB
600 1934 1382 (      1. an empty string will be found anywhere, so will always return `pos'.) 1382 SB
600 1983 1330 (      2. passing in a pos that is too large is not an error, unlike most other) 1330 SB
600 2032 1447 (functions in this class.  Instead, it fails to match and returns NPOS. This is not) 1447 SB
600 2081 1447 (explicit, but requires careful reading of the definition to figure out.  However,) 1447 SB
600 2130 1459 (rule 2 takes precidence over rule 1, so that searching for the empty string at an) 1459 SB
600 2179 563 (illegal position is _not_ found.) 563 SB
600 2277 1428 (\223I have three problems with this.  First, making such boundary conditions or) 1428 SB
600 2326 1414 (error conditions implicit rather than explicit will mean that users don't get a) 1414 SB
600 2375 1437 (clear quick answer, and implementors may miss something and implement it) 1437 SB
600 2424 1462 (incorrectly.  I doubt many will realize that 2 takes precidence over 1 above, for) 1462 SB
600 2473 1446 (example, and may happen to get it backwards.  Second, the treatment of `pos') 1446 SB
600 2522 1391 (values out of range is inconsistant with the rest of the class.  Third, it saves) 1391 SB
600 2571 1402 (nothing in the implementation.  Although as written it would seem that the) 1402 SB
600 2620 1485 (boundary condition of pos out of range is handled naturally if you implement it) 1485 SB
600 2669 1481 (the way it reads, that is not the case.  The size_t domain cannot handle negative) 1481 SB
600 2718 1452 (numbers, and the "natural" behavior is an incorrect result.  Instead, an explicit) 1452 SB
600 2767 1446 (test for the value of pos is needed in the code, before proceeding with the real) 1446 SB
600 2816 1397 (work.  As long as this test is necessary anyway, why not just throw a range) 1397 SB
600 2865 1390 (error?  Returning NPOS saves nothing in the implementation efficiency for) 1390 SB
600 2914 500 (normal in-range searches.\224) 500 SB
1 #C
