300 1547 95 (Title:) 95 SB
600 1547 785 (Specification of traits class is constraining.) 785 SB
300 1596 145 (Section:) 145 SB
600 1596 542 (21.1.1.1 [lib.string.char.traits]) 542 SB
300 1645 125 (Status:) 125 SB
600 1645 110 (active) 110 SB
300 1694 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 1743 699 (In private email, John Dlugosz wrote:) 699 SB
600 1792 1468 (\223The austerity of the traits class strongly suggests certain implementations and) 1468 SB
600 1841 1471 (prevents certain optimizations.  For a simple example, the copy\(\) function does) 1471 SB
600 1890 1433 (not provide for overlapping copies.  Say I have a string "ABr" where A and B) 1433 SB
600 1939 1422 (represent substrings of  some length, and r is unused reserve area.  I want to) 1422 SB
600 1988 1385 (insert "C" into  the string, and the length of "ACB" fits into the pre-existing) 1385 SB
600 2037 1463 (allocation  \(because C is shorter or equal in size to r\).  I can't just copy B  down) 1463 SB
600 2086 1421 (to the tail end.  Instead, I have to reallocate the whole string  and copy the A) 1421 SB
600 2135 173 (part also.) 173 SB
600 2233 1496 (\223More significantly, the find\(\) functions pretty much have to be implemented by) 1496 SB
600 2282 1398 (a brute-force approach as they are defined-- locate a place where the match) 1398 SB
600 2331 1430 (occurs.  In short, I wish the traits available were richer.  It seems inconsistant) 1430 SB
